<dl id="n06129f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06129f">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06129f"> 129(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> takes nails out of <font face="wake">+</font> / insult saint</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">De tels r&eacute;cits me donn&egrave;rent de bonne heure le go&ucirc;t de la mythologie. La na&iuml;vet&eacute; avec laquelle on les prenait reportait &agrave; des milliers d&apos;ann&eacute;es en arri&egrave;re. On me conta la fa&ccedil;on dont mon p&egrave;re, dans son enfance, fut gu&eacute;ri de la fi&egrave;vre. Le matin, avant le jour, on le conduisit &agrave; la chapelle du saint qui en gu&eacute;rissait. Un forgeron vint en m&ecirc;me temps, avec sa forge, ses clous, ses tenailles. Il alluma son fourneau, rougit ses tenailles, et, mettant le fer rouge devant la figure du saint: &ldquo;Si tu ne tires pas la fi&egrave;vre &agrave; cet enfant, dit-il, je vais te ferrer comme un cheval.&rdquo; Le saint ob&eacute;it sur-le-champ. La sculpture en bois a &eacute;t&eacute; longtemps florissante en Bretagne. Ces statues de saints sont d&apos;un r&eacute;alisme &eacute;tonnant; pour des imaginations plastiques, elles vivent. Je me souviens d&apos;un brave homme, pas beaucoup plus fou que les autres, qui s&apos;&eacute;chappait quand il pouvait, le soir. Le matin, on le trouvait dans les &eacute;glises en bras de chemise, suant sang et eau. Il avait pass&eacute; la nuit <mark>&agrave; d&eacute;clouer les <font color="green">[86]</font> christs en croix</mark> et &agrave; tirer les fl&egrave;ches du corps des saint S&eacute;bastien. <font color="green">[Such stories gave me an early taste of mythology. The naivety with which they were taken carried back thousands of years back. I was told how my father, in his childhood, was cured of fever. In the morning, before daylight, he was taken to the chapel of the saint who was a healer. A blacksmith came at the same time, with his forge, his nails, his pincers. He lit his stove, blushed his pincers, and, putting the red hot iron in front of the saint&apos;s face: &ldquo;If you do not take this child&apos;s fever,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I&apos;ll shoe you like a horse.&rdquo; The saint obeys immediately. The wooden sculpture has been flourishing for a long time in Brittany. These statues of saints are astonishingly realistic; for plastic fantasies, they live. I remember a good man, not much crazier than the others, who escaped when he could, in the evening. In the morning, he was found in churches in shirt-sleeves, sweating blood and water. He had spent the night untying the christians crosses and drawing arrows from the body of St. Sebastian.]</font> <small> Ernest Renan, <a name="ERSD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ERSD"><cite title="source">Souvenirs d'enfance et de jeunesse</cite></a> (1883) 86</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
